content.description: Crank up a hollow but solid flake on the arete before making some cruxy edging and palming up the rest of the arete. Well protected, a bit thoughtful, and fun!This was first done as a mixed bolt and gear line, with the lower flake taking the gear. In 2018 it was fully retro-bolted by Rhicard (FA party).Â
content.location: On the far left arete of the Lobo Wall.

climbs.name: Two Old Dogs At The Hydrant

content.description: This climb is fairly sustained at the grade and has great air as it climbs the arete.  A little odd at the bottom as you need to climb around to the right of a big block around the third bolt to get on top of it.
content.location: Starts right of the long obvious arete at the Kennel.  The Kennel is reached by descending from Punch and Judy to the Lobo Wall. Now work left 100 feet or so until you can work back right to the downhill side of the Lobo Wall.

climbs.name: True Grit
climbs.fa: Eric Fazio-Rhicard, Chris Henze, Mike Brogan

content.description: Face climb, pretty thin most of the way up.  Crux is near the middle.  This climb lives up to its name: there is lots of loose grit to kick off, even 17 years after the FA.  Shares anchors with Bierhenkels For Bazzi's.
content.location: Righthand route on the leftmost Canine tower.  Starts near a tree at a good flat belay spot.

climbs.name: Screwed the Pooch
climbs.fa: George Dean, Nate Morgan, Kevin Carmichael

content.description: Decent climbing on smaller stuff to start, thin in the middle, bigger holds up higher.  Goes over bulge near top.
content.location: On the NE side of Lobo Wall, first route left of the obvious chimney with a tree in it.

content.description: A mellow face with no certain crux. Mostly solid rock and good holds define the route, which is the easiest route of any quality on the wall.
content.protection: Perhaps 8(?) bolts to one chain and one rap hanger. Rap, do not lower.
content.location: This route lies on the lower side of Lobo Wall. The approach to the base around the north side is loose and steep, but requires only about 10 minutes to reach with a light pack on.   From the right (north) end of the E/SE face of Lobo Wall walk Southward to a crescent shaped flake a few feet from the wall and 2 meters high. Start from said flake and stay on the left-most of 2 diverging bolt lines.

content.description: A fairly mellow climb with the crux on the lower portion in thinner holds and small friction for feet. Worth doing, but not great.
content.protection: about 7 (?) bolts to an anchor with a chain and rap hanger. Rap, do not lower.
content.location: This route lies on the lower side of Lobo Wall. The approach to the base around the north side is loose and steep, but requires only about 10 minutes to reach with a light pack on.   From the right (north) end of the E/SE face of Lobo Wall this is the second bolted line in total. The first, 'Cookie Duster Roy' actually lies just to the right around the blunt arete, on the N/NE face.

content.description: A slightly harder and less secure route for the wall, but still worth doing. The crux comes low as you split right from "Schroedinger's Cat" on crimps and slopers to escape to a different path. staying left and crossing higher might be slightly easier.
content.protection: Perhaps 8 bolts to a chain and rap hanger. Rap, do not lower.
content.location: This route lies on the lower side of Lobo Wall. The approach to the base around the north side is loose and steep, but requires only about 10 minutes to reach with a light pack on.   From the right (north) end of the E/SE face of Lobo Wall walk Southward to a crescent shaped flake a few feet from the wall and 2 meters high. Start from said flake and stay on the right-most of 2 diverging bolt lines.

content.description: This is a pretty fun 5.9 route that protects well.  There is a nice hand crack in the middle and a tricky bulge near the top.  It is pretty sustained at the grade.
content.protection: cams up to Camalot #2 and some nuts
content.location: series of cracks left of a bolted 5.8 and right of a bolted 5.10

content.description: Start in the main crack until you can follow a thin crack to the hueco (cool rest if you can find it) and then up discontinuous thin cracks. Try not to go too far right. The crack will fizzle out where a couple of face moves will get you to an unseen bolt just below the final bulge. Pull this to the chains.
content.protection: Mostly small stuff: 0tcu-1BD, nuts/brass, 1 bolt. Chain anchor. A black alien or similar was helpful, but probably not necessary.
content.location: Left end of the west side (uphill) of Lobo Wall.  Locate a 2' hueco near the far left end of the wall. The route goes up the cracks in the face just to the right of the big crack/chimney.

content.description:
This route is only for those seeking a meaningless death on a poorly bolted, crumb cake of a climb.  The first of the randomly placed bolts is 15 feet off the ground, above a ledge, and awkward.  20 more feet of climbing on eroding rock leads to the second bolt. 

  Note "Squeezing the Lemmon II" (2000, EFR) lists this climb as 5.10 with no safety caveats.  The above is merely my flamebait of an opinion.  I believe this route should be rebolted or removed.
content.location: Look for the only bolted line on the furthest North (down highway) Canine.  The route climbs the less steep East face.

content.description: Start is slabby going into a wide crack. Getting around the wide crack is a bit awkward, but there are jugs.
Steep face climbing past a series of dikes.  Finish guarded by a tricky bulge.
content.protection: Handful of draws.  Shares anchors for Nickel Puppies.
content.location: On the north side of the Lobo wall.  The bolted route immediately left of Nickel Puppies.

content.description: Walk out on a small ledge past Valdez is Coming to a bolt that should be within arms reach. Continue up the thin face. Difficult side pulls, gastons and crimps.
content.location: First bolted line on the left face of the Lobo Wall.

content.description: A strenuous boulder problem down low leads to a brief undercling traverse and a large breadloaf lieback to the chains.
content.location: Left of Hippo Space Invaders.

climbs.name: Hippo Space Invaders
climbs.fa: Eric Fazio-Rhicard, Bernt Prause, Uschi Prause

content.description: After a tricky start moving to and past the first bolt, climb the arete.  It is a short climb and the formation resembles a tooth.
content.location: the southwest arete of the second small spire (from the west) directly north of Lobo Wall

content.description: Thin start leads to easier climbing above
content.location: Climber's right of "Foreign Affair"

content.description: Bouldery crux somewhere on this route..
content.location: On north side of Lobo Wall, first route right of the chimney next to "Screwed the Pooch"..

content.description:
Start off up an easy slab and then crimp your way up a gently overhanging face. A fun route that boils down to two one-move boulder problems in the V5-7 range: both involve long moves off of small holds. You do 12a/b climbing up to the first crux, get an excellent rest, fire the second crux, and then cruise to the top. 

  If I recall correctly, the whole thing is less than 20 moves, but it's action-packed. 

  Nothing to write home about, but if you've got strong fingers and weak endurance, it's probably worth your attention. Climbs much better than it looks.
content.protection: 4 bolts -- bring four quickdraws. Currently, the anchors are too far behind the cliff to lower off, so you'll want to top the rig out and walk off the backside. Baker promises to fix new anchors soon, though, so your mileage may vary.
content.location: The route is on the southern face of the eastern most Canine. Aptly named.

content.description: A fun route originally bolted by John Baker in 2011. The rock below the first bolt is a bit crumbly, but the rest of the route provides great movement on some interesting holds.
content.protection: The first 15-20 feet of rock isn't great quality and is hard to protect- this can be avoided by either a very long stick clip to the first bolt, or by placing some small gear in the questionable rock.    7 bolts & chains
content.location: This route is on the furthest Canine Tower, next to "Leaners Permit".

content.description: One of the better lines on the lower (S/SE) side of Lobo Wall. Climb a slightly difficult face with side-pulls or jams to a 3 foot roof with jugs, then saunter on up to the top.
content.protection: Perhaps 7(?) bolts to a single chain and rap hanger.   Rap, do not lower.
content.location: This route lies on the lower side of Lobo Wall. The approach to the base around the north side is loose and steep, but requires only about 10 minutes to reach with a light pack on.   From the right (north) end of the E/SE face of Lobo Wall walk Southward to the 6th route, which has a roof 20 feet off the ground and is just before a large slot in a corner.

content.description: Fun route on the right side of the arete, around the corner from Puddin' Britches.

climbs.name: Butchwax
climbs.fa: Chris Henze, Kevin Carmichael, & Tejal Parikh (1990)

content.description:
Delicately climb a less-than-vertical face using small edges and nubs past two bolts.  When the angle steepens pull through a short powerful crux on pockets and edges to obtain a rest at a platform.  Two short sections of face and a second platform lead to the chains. 

Butchwax is a pleasant enough romp on interesting features but ultimately too short and inconsistent to leave a lasting impression.  Depending on your body type and climbing strengths the route may feel a bit soft for the established grade.
content.protection:
6 bolts to chain anchors.  The bolts are stamped with the initials 'BWM'.  Since the anchors are recessed, long slings and rappelling are recommended. 

  While Squeezing The Lemmon II suggests a light rack, I believe this is a fully bolted sport climb.  A small cam or nut could be placed between bolts 5 and 6 but it would not serve much purpose.
content.location: Butchwax is located on the third pinnacle from the west.  Butchwax climbs the east face while Flat Top climbs the south.

climbs.name: Bierhenkels For Bazzi's
climbs.fa: Bernt Prause, Uschi Prause, Eric Fazio-Rhicard

content.description: Only 30 feet tall, but there's no waiting for the full-value 5.10.  Thin start up to pretty high first bolt, goes right of bulge, then slightly steep moves on positive holds to top.  Pretty much starts in the tree.  Avoiding a branch in your butt is the key to the start.  Shares anchors with True Grit.  Fun climbing, would probably get another star if only it were taller.  Call it a star and a half.
content.location: Lefthand route on leftmost Canine tower.  Starts on the arete, pretty much in the tree.

content.description: Four little pinnacles and a wall with 30 routes from 5.5 to 5.13.  Many of the climbs are in the 5.10 range.  Most lines are bolted, but there are gear routes as well.  Pretty easy to follow the sun or shade depending on the season.  The walls face SE or NW.  Lots of large rocks and trees for belay seats, shade, etc.
